name: 9-acetylanthracene
Reason: The anthracene unit has an original melting point of around 218°C, as a basic unit. The acetylation of the anthracene slightly decreases this melting point due to the potential for disrupting the crystal lattice of the solid anthracene, although acetyl groups generally increase hydrophobicity and can contribute to pi stacking interactions. The acetyl group is relatively small and its electron-withdrawing nature (due to the carbonyl group) is likely to have only a modest effect on the melting point. Given that the acetyl group could potentially provide some additional rigidity to the structure, one might expect the melting point to decrease. Estimating an effect of -140°C for the disruption caused by the acetylation (since it prevents effective pi stacking and close packing of molecules like in anthracene) results in an expected melting point close to the actual value.
